This is a known breaking change. .NET MAUI 10 adopts Android's **edge-to-edge** display by default, which means `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (already deprecated at API 30) no longer drives layout. Instead, you handle **keyboard insets**.

### Quick fix — use `KeyboardAccelerator` padding via insets

**1. In `AndroidManifest.xml`, keep `adjustResize`:**
```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

**2. In your page/view, react to keyboard insets.** The simplest cross-platform approach in .NET 10 is to bind your bottom padding to the safe-area inset:

```xml
<!-- ChatPage.xaml -->
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1"
                           Padding="{OnPlatform Android='0,0,0,0'}"
                           x:Name="InputBar">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

**3. Handle the inset in your platform code (`Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`):**

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Listen for keyboard (IME) inset changes
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav-bar height
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|---|---|
| `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` shrank the window | Edge-to-edge: window stays full-size |
| Layout auto-adjusted | You consume `WindowInsets` to add padding |

The insets listener fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes and pushes your input bar up by exactly the keyboard height. This is the same pattern Google recommends for native Android apps post-API 30.
